segments.text: Okay, you were mentioning an example.
As an example.
Hold on just a minute.
Lead us away.
From the Soviets?
Is that what you were saying?
British attempts?
Yeah, lead us away from the Soviets.
Okay, and that's the Fulton County, that was an example.
Yeah, no, this is an example that I intended to mention.
Notwithstanding the black book, the sign with Churchill, Stalin, and Roosevelt, at Yalta, provided that immediately after the Germans capitulated,
a reparations commission would meet in Moscow with a delegation from Britain, the United States, and one from Russia would convene and deal on the subject of German reparations.
Mr. Truman's thought policy was, after Roosevelt's passage,
that he would count all of Roosevelt's commitments.
And our job was to count one of them, namely to join the assembly of this commission at Moscow immediately after the Germans capitulated.
Well, we hurriedly formed our mission to that end.
And we stopped in London.
Two plane loads of us stopped in London on our way over.
And we had a visit with the British.
And they asked us, why are you in a hurry?
And they just attempted to dissuade us from the immediate German movement to Moscow.
of course we responded that we had no choice, that this commitment had been made by our previous administration, Mr. Truman, and said they wanted us carried out.
And we left them with no assurance whatsoever that they were going to meet us in Moscow.
And it was surprising to me that in the first place
They even tried to dissuade us from going ahead.
But when we got to Moscow, we took time enough to go over the ruins of Germany.
We spent a few days at Frankfurt.
And we divided ourselves up into groups of three to an automobile.
We covered practically all the ruins of Germany as far east as Leipzig.
And we went on to Moscow.
We got to Moscow.
The Russians did appear.
The British did appear.
So I would say there's something to that thinking.
I'm sure Dr. Anderson will appreciate that.
Briefly, how was it working with the British in this time period?
I know you've answered some of that in what you've discussed.
Can you briefly sum up how it was to work with the British
and how it was to work with the Soviets.
No relationship between the two, but straight-line British, straight-line Soviets.
How was it to work with them in this time period?
Well, it was both presented difficulty, but the difficulty with the Russians arose largely from the standpoint or the fact
that they had little delegated authority.
And they were deathly afraid of the British.
The Russians were deathly afraid of the British.
because the British, they said, had invaded them twice in this century.
And from a standpoint of the British, the difficulty arose from a different source.
That was all Foreign Service,
procedures and activities of the British and has historically moved with a great deal of sophistication and a well-informed group of servicemen.
They knew exactly what they wanted to do.
and well organized, smoothly organized.
They had a disposition of not wanting to give the Germans any reparations whatsoever.
And that was very influential on, I'd say, a majority of our group.
Does that answer your question?
That answers the Great Britain.
With the Soviets, you said there were problems with them.
Getting back to the Soviet side, they expressed a great admiration for the Americans because the Americans fought
seceded from Great Britain and fought the War of Independence and won it and had done very well.
And they likened themselves to the Americans because they too fought a very difficult breach from the Tsars and had had a
in holding things together.
But the chief trouble in dealing with the Russians always clearly stemmed from the fact that they had to go back to headquarters for the answer to every question.
It took time.
required a lot of patience.
They were very courteous to us in the summer of 1945.
There is, I'd say more so before the bombing
came into existence.
But I've always thought that the Cold War started at Muscat, at Ushtown.
With Truman's statement about the bombing of T. Scotland.
Yeah.
On a more personal note, after the war,
up to now.
It's been said that you have been an advocate of liberal politics in the state of Texas for some time, and up to today's Texas Democratic politics.
Could you discuss your involvement with the evolution of liberal politics in this state?
And you might include
Any involvement with LBJ?
Well, I'll say that I've always figured that this democracy of ours could not go forward
without the exercise of a good deal of liberalism.
On the other hand, I've always exercised the independence of an action that is conservative.
I believe in a balanced budget.
I don't think you can run any kind of an institution successfully without a balanced budget and I'm not a liberal to the point of way you give away everything you've got to do things with reason
And I've always been a Democrat.
My first vote as a Democrat was for Woodrow Wilson when I was at the University of Texas Law School.
And I think I voted for every Democratic president since.
That includes Carlin.
That includes Carlin both times.
And I'll do the same thing this year, regardless of who it is.
But I got out of my early study of government the definite feeling that you couldn't have a continuation of a democracy if we had a free society.
without the exercise of a good deal of liberalism.
I think the word, what I wanted to live with was everything is white and overplayed.
I remember my wife told me one time that she had just read in the Chicago Tribune a story about a great liberal

It seems that some prominent Republican had written the chairman of the National Republican Committee and told him that he wanted to give some money to the Republican Party, but he was disturbed because there wasn't a single liberal ever heard of in the ranks of the Republicans.
And the chairman of the Republican committee promptly wrote the man back and told him that as an example of a liberal, he wanted to cite J. Howard Pugh as just having given the committee $50,000.
And I think that is illustrating some people's views of what makes a conservative and what makes a liberal.

the digits of life um now it's the lyndon johnson i met lyndon johnson early in the office of governor james v already he invited me to his office to meet lyndon he just announced for congress from the austin district where buckhannon the incumbent
congressman had died.
And I asked London what his platform was and he said in the first place he was going to help Roosevelt pack the court.
Well, I had been through the School of Government at the University of Texas and the law school and I was pretty well steeped in the
in the propriety of the checks and powers in government.
And I scolded him.
I said he shouldn't do that because it's wrong for one department of the Constitutional Department of the government to try to hobble another department.
He went on and advocated the packet in the court and got elected.
And later on I supported him when he ran for the Senate and I supported him when he announced for and did run for President of the United States.
I was at Los Angeles and when he
was requested by John F. Kennedy after he was nominated to join him on the ticket.
And Johnson had the difficult decision to make as to whether he would or wouldn't.
And everybody I knew in Texas and Los Angeles preferred that Lyndon stay in the Senate.
He was majority leader.
But I know Mr. Raymond expressed that feeling.
Later in the day, Mr. Raymond told me that John F. Kennedy had come to see him and told him that he needed Lyndon to win the election.
Needed him on the team.
Needed to help him carry the South.
And appealed to Mr. Raymond.
that it was a matter of duty because 25 other Democratic senators had joined him in the request of London to join the ticket, and that as many congressmen had done the same thing.
Mr. Raven told me that he finally said to John, well, John, since you put it that way,
And if you'll get on that TV and tell the world that this is your idea, you are drafting Lyndon to go on the ticket with you, I'd recommend you do it.
And John did make the statement, Mr. Raymond required that Lyndon join the ticket.
And I thought Lyndon did the right thing.
because he owed it to the Democratic Party and he owed it to the nominee in that respect.
And I know that it wasn't very comforting to Bobby when John asked him when Lennon accepted.
That was unfortunate.
But I knew Lennon well.
I was with him through
his campaigns as Senator and President, and respected him very well.
I couldn't agree with him on his Vietnam policy.
I thought Lyndon was misled by the military.
Did I answer your question?
That's correct.
Could you briefly discuss your involvement with the JFK administration?
It was very brief because I was suffering at that time recovering from a broken bone
right lower leg, right lower leg.
And President Kennedy asked me to come up and help.
The new Secretary, appointed Secretary of the Interior, organized his oil and gas department.
And I agreed to and did.
go up to do it.
And after just six or eight weeks time I had finished that chore and then came back home.
And that was about the consent of the service that I rented on that occasion.
I put in more time for Mr. Truman when his Secretary of Interior was organizing the oil and gas office to meet the emergencies of the Korean War.
I put in six, eight months of
of organizing and establishing the Petroleum Administration for Defense.
I had previously been there with Ickes as his director of transportation when Harold Ickes was administrator of the Petroleum Administration for War.
And I put about three years on it.
Right now, you are on the Board of Advisors of the Center for Defense Information.
Pardon me?
You're on the Board of Advisors of the Center for Defense Information right now.
Are you not?
No, I'm not active anymore.
I've given up those assignments.
You gave up those assignments?
Yeah, I'm giving up those assignments.
No involvement with them?
Pardon me?
There's no involvement with the Center for Defense Information now?
Well, I'm advising, but I'm not an active participant.
I'm not on the board of directors.
I'm not an active participant, but I do support them.
I communicate with them, but I don't attend regular meetings.
What does CDI stand for right now?
CDI stands for the Center for Defense Information.
It's run by the leading officer there is Admiral Gene LaRock, a very able man.
He's doing a commendable job.
He's supported by retired Admiral Carroll, and he's got three or four generals in the organization.
is doing a very effective work in research and giving authoritative answers to defense questions, answers respected even by the Pentagon, by the members of Congress.
A lot of members of Congress communicate with them and rely upon them.
And they take no part in politics whatsoever.
They are not a political organization.
It's simply a research and fact-finding institution.
I'm also a sponsor of and a consultant with another organization in Washington.
It's called the
The moving spirit in that is Admiral Gaylor, Noel Gaylor.
And the chairman of that board is George
I'm the celebrated Poland ambassador to Russia, George Kennan.
And the co-chairman is Bob McNamara.
And I work with that organization.
They do a different kind of work.
It's fact-finding, too.
They get a little closer to politics than CDI does.
Two organizations complement one another.
The style of this organization is the Committee on East-West Accord.
And the design of that institution has been defined and recommends some alternatives to the president's nonpartisan
Republicans and Democrats on it.
Some alternatives to suggest to the Reagan administration.
I don't know that he's ever took a recommendation yet.
Might be.

But.
something that just popped into my head that you might want to say on the record.
Is there anything you would like to say to college students?
What?

To college students, the younger people of today, with your views, what you advocate, the course that you see America heading in, what could you say to college students who might direct that course for tomorrow?
Is there anything you can say to him?
Something that you would like to say to me now?
Jeff, here are some general thoughts.
Something to think about.
The thing I would say to college students is to fortify your education by basing it upon a good, solid liberal arts
education and let the choice of your profession, of your career, be decided after that base is established.
Thank you very much.
It's been a most gratifying interview.
